arly delineated context and question, is the key to building a reliable and trustworthy RAG-based AI like Koda. Enhanced Ingestion Pipeline: Intelligent Document Processing The standard RAG ingestion pipeline is effective, but the Koda blueprint outlines a more sophisticated, multi-stage approach: the Enhanced Ingestion & Intelligence Pipeline. This system is designed to be more accurate, efficient, and actionable than a simple text-tovector pipeline. It introduces concepts of triage, conditional processing, and structured data extraction to transform the ingestion process from a passive indexing task into an active intelligence-gathering operation. This section will deconstruct the four stages of this enhanced pipeline: Pre-processing & Triage, Conditional Deep Analysis, Intelligent Filing & Validation, and Indexing & Action Triggers. We will provide a detailed technical implementation guide and world-class prompts for each stage. Step 1: Pre-processing & Triage This initial stage acts as an intelligent gatekeeper for the more resource-intensive parts of the pipeline. Its purpose is to quickly assess an incoming document, extract its basic text, and make a cost-effective decision about how to handle it. This prevents the system from wasting expensive GPU cycles on low-quality scans or irrelevant documents. Technical Implementation: OCR & Text Extraction: As in the standard RAG pipeline, this step uses OCR and text extraction tools to get the raw text from the document. The key difference here is the emphasis on speed and efficiency. A faster, less resource-intensive OCR model might be used at this stage, with the option to use a more powerful model later if needed. Rapid Classification: Once the text is extracted, it is fed to a small, highly-optimized classification model. This is not a large, general-purpose LLM. Instead, it should be a fine-tuned model (like a distilled BERT or a similar transformer-based classifier) trained specifically to identify the document